Somocystinamide A is a potent antitumor lipopeptide with one disulphide bond. Biosynthetically it is produced as a secondary metabolite by a mixed enzymatic system: nonribosomal peptide synthetase (NRPS) and polyketide synthase (KPS) [43]. This highly acid-sensitive lipopeptide was purified from a cyanobacteria Lyngbya majuscule. Significant cytotoxic activity of somocystinamide A was found against mouse neuro-2a neuroblastoma cells. Later, the anticancer and antiangiogenic activities of this lipopeptide were demonstrated against leukemia, lung carcinoma, breast carcinoma and prostate carcinoma cell lines [6] (Table 2
                        ). It induced apoptosis in Jurkat and leukemia cells through caspase-8 activation and PARP cleavage (Fig. 1a). The study conducted by Wrasidlo et al. 
                        [6] demonstrated whether somocystinamide A could induce apoptosis on wild-type and caspase-8-deficient Jurkat cells. It was found that caspase-8-deficient Jurkat cells were undergoing less apoptosis compared with wild-type cells indicating a selective role of caspase-8 in apoptosis induced by somocystinamide A. Further, it potently blocked endothelial cell tube formation in vitro and blood vessel growth in a zebrafish experiment demonstrating an antiangiogenic property of somocystinamide A.
